		<div id="Q1" class="reveal-modal">
		<h2>How do I decide if I’m a beginner or an experienced amateur?</h2>
		<p>The EAC Art Awards aim to attract entries from people who have taken up art in later life; perhaps whilst still at work or after retirement. Typically such artists have not earned their living either now or in the past, through their art.</p>
		<p>We do welcome entries from artists who make some money from sales and commissions. Clearly they would be ‘more experienced / semi-professional artists’. Those who have recently – say within the last 2 to 3 years – taken up their interest are more likely to come under the umbrella ‘ beginner / less-experienced amateur.</p>
		<a class="close-reveal-modal">&#215;</a>
	</div>
	
	<div id="Q2" class="reveal-modal">
		<h2>I am not sure whether my work is good enough to enter?</h2>
		<p>In recognition of the wide range of ability and talent that exists within the label of ‘amateur’ artist, we now have two prizes for each category, beginner and experienced amateur. On the entry form we ask you to self select the group that best describes you and you will be entered for that prize. Our ambition is to encourage artists of all abilities and levels of experience to have a go and enjoy taking part. We also welcome entries from those who have produced a collaborative piece of work.</p>
		<a class="close-reveal-modal">&#215;</a>
	</div>
	
	<div id="Q3" class="reveal-modal">
		<h2>Where does the entry money go?</h2>
		<p>EAC is a charity and the EAC Art Awards do not make a profit – in fact they generally make a financial loss. The entry fee goes some way towards our organisational and administrative costs. This year we have held the fee at £5 per entry  - the same as in 1995 - due to this year’s generous sponsorship by the John Ellerman Foundation.</p>
		<a class="close-reveal-modal">&#215;</a>
	</div>
	
	<div id="Q4" class="reveal-modal">
		<h2>I work in textile/mosaic/decoupage. Can I enter my work in EAC Art Awards?</h2>
		<p>We accept any medium and you will need to be able to photograph your work. We welcome entries that are to your individual design (and not made from a kit). We aim to be inclusive and to celebrate creativity and talent in whatever material you use.</p>
		<a class="close-reveal-modal">&#215;</a>
	</div>
	
	<div id="Q5" class="reveal-modal">
		<h2>I don’t live in ‘later life’ housing; can I still enter the competition?</h2>
		<p>Yes, all amateur and semi-professional artists over 60 can enter, but those who live in sheltered/retirement housing or care homes and people who enter from a day centre have the additional benefit of being considered for the Angela Farnell prize. This is awarded in memory of the founder of EAC.</p>
		<a class="close-reveal-modal">&#215;</a>
	</div>
	
	<div id="Q6" class="reveal-modal">
		<h2>A group of us work together in a care home, led by an art therapist. Can we enter our collaborative work?</h2>
		<p>Yes, the Prize for Group Work is specifically for collaborative work, with or without the leadership of an artist or art therapist. The prize is not intended for art groups where the individual members complete their own individual works, but is intended for a larger-scale joint piece of work to which all members have made a contribution.</p>
		<a class="close-reveal-modal">&#215;</a>
	</div>
	
	<div id="Q7" class="reveal-modal">
		<h2>What is the "Well-being" prize?</h2>
		<p>This is a new optional Award. We want to demonstrate how art may have helped people to manage a difficult life event. Perhaps you belong to an Art Therapy group or maybe you took up art following a bereavement, loss or illness. We ask you to provide a short summary of how art has helped you to overcome difficulties or given you a new interest.</p>
		<a class="close-reveal-modal">&#215;</a>
	</div>
	
	<div id="Q8" class="reveal-modal">
		<h2>I have heard that the Art Awards is moving towards an online event. I don’t use a computer. Can I still enter?</h2>
		<p>Yes, we accept postal entries and they are treated equally to online entries. However, we wish to encourage those less familiar with the internet to develop new skills, and therefore, if possible, we encourage you to enter online. Family members or local libraries are a great resource. Do take a look at our new website, which we hope is very user friendly. There is nothing like the excitement of viewing your own work on the world wide web!
We check incoming entries, and an EAC Art Awards volunteer is available for support.</p>
		<a class="close-reveal-modal">&#215;</a>
	</div>
	
	<div id="Q9" class="reveal-modal">
		<h2>I am not sure which category my work falls into?</h2>
		<p>There are 8 possible categories and we ask that you choose the one that you think is most applicable; you will then be entered for that prize. It is likely that some people will find that their work could fall into more than one category, in which case just choose the one that you would prefer to enter.</p>
		<a class="close-reveal-modal">&#215;</a>
	</div>
	
	<div id="Q10" class="reveal-modal">
		<h2>I don’t use a computer; can I vote for the People's Choice Award by telephone or post?</h2>
		<p>Unfortunately we can only accept votes online. We have found that many people have successfully got round this by asking family, friends, neighbours or housing scheme managers to support them! It is a great way to get grandchildren involved and interested in your work. Remember that there are other prizes that you will qualify for.</p>
		<a class="close-reveal-modal">&#215;</a>
	</div>

  
  
  
